The Australian government strongly opposes Japanese whaling in the Antarctic whale sanctuary, pushing for a ban on all forms of whaling.
Prime Minister Howard challenges Japan's claim of needing to expand whale kills for research.
Despite diplomatic efforts, Japan remains firm on continuing whaling for research purposes.
Australia and New Zealand are exploring legal avenues to stop Japan's whale hunting.
The International Whaling Commission banned commercial whaling in 1986, but Japan and Norway continue under scientific programs.
Animal rights groups are considering appealing to the World Court to halt Japan's plans to kill humpback whales.
